Anatomy of a simple ggplot

ggplot2




  • ggplot() creates a coordinate system that you can add layers to
  • The argument (data = mpg) links the data mpg to the graph.
  • Running only the first piece of this code will create an empty graph.

geoms


  • geom function add layers to the coordinate system created from the ggplot() function.
  • The geom_point() adds a layer of a scatterplot.
  • Each geom function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument.
    • This defines how variables in your dataset are mapped to visual properties
    • the mapping argument is always paired with aes()
    • displ gets mapped to the x-position aesthetic of the points
    • hwy gets mapped to the y-position aesthetic of the points

Aesthetics


  • displ gets mapped to the x-position aesthetic of the points
  • hwy gets mapped to the y-position aesthetic of the points

Aesthetics


  • An aesthetic is a visual property of the objects in your plot
  • You can convey information about your data by mapping the aesthetics in your plot to the variables in your dataset.
  • Aesthetics include:
    • x-position, y-position
    • size, shape, and color of your points.

Aesthetics: Your turn

  • Type ?geom_point to see what aesthetics can be used in geom_point
  • Plot displ vs hwy:
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
  • Now can we map the variable class to the color of the points to distinguish between different types of cars?

Answer

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy,color = class))

Color mappings

More aesthetics

We can try other aesthetics: size, alpha, and shape

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Note the warning for using an unordered variable with an ordered aesthetic

alpha

alpha controls opacity

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

A warning again

shape

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

Categorical variables

  • Categorical (qualitative) variables contain a finite number of categories or distinct groups
    • Nominal variables have no intrinsic ordering to its categories, e.g., gender
    • Ordinal variables have intrinsic ordering to its categories, e.g., education level (high school, BS, MS, PhD)

Numerical variables

  • Numerical (quantitative) variables are expressed in terms of numbers rather than natural language descriptions.
    • Discrete variables are numeric variables that have a countable number of values, e.g., age, number of students in a class
    • Continuous Variabels are numeric variables that have an infinite number of values between any two values, e.g., height, weight

Aesthetics vs. arguments

You can also set the aesthetic properties of your geom manually. For example, we can make all of the points in our plot red:

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "red")

Aesthetics vs. arguments

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "red")

In the above code red is the argument of the geom function, not of the aes(), because we do not need to associate color with a variable in the mpg data.

To set an aesthetic manually, set the aesthetic by name as an argument of your geom function, for example:

- The name of a color as a character string
- The size of a point in mm
- The shape of a point as a number

Common problems and some tips

R is extremely picky, and a misplaced character can make all the difference. As you start to run R code, you are likely to run into problems. Don’t worry — it happens to everyone.

  • Make sure that every ( is matched with a ) and every ” is paired with another ”
  • For ggplot2 graphics, `+’ has to come at the end of the line, not the start.
  • If you are still stuck, try the help. You can get help about any R function by running ?function_name in the console
  • Read the error message. If you cannot understand it, google it.

Making reproducible code

  1. Packages should be loaded at the top of the script, so it’s easy to see which ones the example needs.
    • This is a good time to check that you’re using the latest version of each package.
  2. Spend a little bit of time ensuring that your code is easy for others to read:
    • Make sure you’ve used spaces and your variable names are concise, yet informative
    • Use comments to indicate where your problem lies
    • Do your best to remove everything that is not related to the problem. The shorter your code is, the easier it is to understand and fix.
